# Public Prosecutor _v_ Eng Heng Choon  

### \[2022\] SGMC 52

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">Case No. 216117777711-1, Magistrate's Appeals No 9142/2022/01</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">31 August 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">Magistrates Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Luke Tan</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Mr Jonathan Lee and Ms Christina Koh for the Public Prosecutor; The accused in person</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Eng Heng Choon</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Law – Offence – Driving without due care and attention

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9142/2022/01.\]

31 August 2022

### District Judge Luke Tan:

## Introduction

1       The accused, Eng Heng Choon, a 44-year-old male Singaporean, faced a charge under s 65(1)(a) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (**“RTA”**), for driving on a road without due care and attention (“careless driving”). The offence, which attracts enhanced punishment under s 65(5)(b) of the RTA because of his previous conviction under s 63(4) of the RTA, reads:

> You….are charged that you, on the 11th day of August 2021, at about 9.00 am, along Bukit Timah Road towards Upper Bukit Timah Road Singapore near Duke’s Road, did drive motor vehicle no SMY 7842 E on a road without due care and attention, to wit, by making an abrupt lane change to your right and encroaching into the path of another motorist driving a black Honda motorcar, causing the latter to brake suddenly to avoid a collision with your vehicle, and you have thereby committed an offence under s 65(1)(a) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”).

> And further that you, before the commission of the said offence, were previously convicted on 3 November 2020 in Court 7B of the State Courts, Singapore, for an offence under s 63(4) of the RTA vide Report No. 206165928811, which conviction has not been set aside, and you are thereby liable to be punished under s 65(5)(b) of the RTA.

2       In essence, the Prosecution’s case was that the accused was travelling along lane three of Bukit Timah Road towards Upper Bukit Timah Road, near Duke’s Road, when he made an abrupt lane switch from lane three to lane two, that is the leftmost lane to the middle lane. Even though the accused had signalled before he made the lane change, he carried out the act without due care and attention because the lane change was made abruptly by his encroaching into the path of another motorist driving a black Honda motor car (the “**black Honda**”). There was also less than one car length distance between his car and the black Honda when he made the lane change, and this had caused the black Honda to brake suddenly to avoid a collision.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

3       The accused claimed trial to the charge.

4       To prove its case, the Prosecution called two witnesses, SGT(3) Mohamad Al Zaki s/o Harun Al Rasheed (“**Sgt Zaki”**), a traffic police (TP) officer who had witnessed the incident, and Senior Staff Sergeant Mohamed Sufian Sudin (“**SSS Sufian**”), the investigation officer for this case.

5       The accused testified in his own defence, and also adduced evidence in support of his case. Having assessed all the evidence, I was of the view that the Prosecution had proven its case against the accused beyond a reasonable doubt and I convicted the accused of the offence. Thereafter, following the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence and having heard the accused’s mitigation, I imposed a fine of $1,000 (in default five days' imprisonment). The accused was also disqualified from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of ten (10) months.

6       The accused has paid his fine, and commenced serving his term of disqualification. However, being dissatisfied, he filed an appeal against his conviction and sentence on 28 July 2022. I now give the reasons for my decision.

## The elements of the charge

7       To prove the charge as drafted, the Prosecution had to establish that:

> (a)     On 11th August 2021, at about 9.00 am, along Bukit Timah Road towards Upper Bukit Timah Road Singapore near Duke’s Road, the accused did drive motor vehicle no SMY 7842 E (“the accused’s car”); and

> (b)     He drove without due care and attention by making an abrupt lane change to his right and encroaching into the path of another motorist driving the black Honda, causing the latter to brake suddenly to avoid a collision with the accused’s car.

8       For the purpose of attracting the enhanced punishment under s 65(5)(b) of the RTA, the Prosecution had inserted details of the accused’s previous conviction for an offence under s 63(4) of the RTA (essentially a “speeding offence”) in the charge. However, at the hearing, I made it clear to the accused that this previous conviction had no bearing on the issue of proof of the present offence under s 65(1)(a) RTA. In any event, the accused confirmed that he did not dispute his previous conviction for his speeding offence.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

9       For the present careless driving offence, as regards proof of the element of driving “without due care and attention”, the observations of the Courts in the following cases are instructive:

> (a)     In _PP v Poh Teck Huat_ <span class="citation">\[2003\] 2 SLR(R) 299</span> (“**_Poh Teck Huat_**”), Yong Pung How CJ at \[17\] accepted the proposition in _Bhalchandra Waman Pathe v The State of Maharashtra_ (1967) 71 Bombay LR 634 that culpable negligence was “acting _without_ the consciousness … that the illegal and mischievous effect will follow, but in circumstances which show that the actor has not exercised the caution incumbent upon him and if he had\[,\] he would have had the consciousness”.

> (b)     In _PP v Hue An Li_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 4 SLR 661</span> _(“_**_Hue An Li_**_”)_, the High Court remarked at \[45\] that the restatement of the definition of _inter alia_ “negligence” enunciated in _Poh Teck Huat_ remain good law. Further, in _Hue An Li_, the High Court at \[51\] made the further tentative observation that what constitutes “without due care and attention” under the RTA, may be akin to what constitutes “negligence” in the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) (“**Penal Code**”).

10     Thus, as regards the element of driving “without due care and attention” in the present charge, I was of the view that it would be sufficient to show that when the accused was driving, he was “acting _without_ the consciousness … that the illegal and mischievous effect will follow but in circumstances which show that he has not exercised the caution incumbent upon him and if he had\[,\] he would have had the consciousness”.

## The Prosecution’s case: Outline of evidence and submissions

11     For purposes of the trial, the following facts were essentially undisputed:

> (a)     The accused had driven his car bearing registration number SMY 7842E at around 9 am on 11 August 2021 along Bukit Timah Road.

> (b)     Prior to the commission of the alleged offence, the accused had one previous conviction in the State Courts. The details of these conviction are that on 3 November 2020, he was convicted of an offence of speeding under Section 63(4) of the RTA (51-60 kmph) vide report no. 206165928811, which conviction has not been set aside. Hence, he was liable to the enhanced penalties under Section 65(5)(b) of the RTA.

12     As regards the other elements of the charge, the Prosecution’s case against the accused centred almost entirely on the evidence of Sgt Zaki, and the documents produced in support of that evidence.

### Abrupt lane switch caused the black Honda to “jam brake”

13     Sgt Zaki is a Traffic Police (TP) officer. As at 11 August 2021, which was the date of the alleged offence, Sgt Zaki has been a patrol officer for about 4 years and 2 months.

14     Sgt Zaki testified that on the material date, he was conducting patrol on his motorcycle. Earlier that morning at about 0845 hours, in the vicinity of Bukit Timah, he had stopped a driver for not wearing a seatbelt in a proper manner and had taken enforcement action against the latter.

15     Thereafter, Sgt Zaki had intended to go to the Bukit Timah Neighbourhood Police Centre to lodge his summons action, when he spotted the accused. This was at about 9am, when Sgt Zaki was riding along the side road of Bukit Timah Road towards Upper Bukit Timah Road. This side road leads to the main Bukit Timah Road. Sgt Zaki said that at that time, his motorcycle was about 4 car-lengths (about 6 to 8 metres[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3)) behind the accused’s car, a black Mercedes. Sgt Zaki was in the same lane as the accused, which was at the extreme left of a three lane road.

16     Sgt Zaki further said that he had a clear and unobstructed view of the accused’s car which was directly in front of him, as there was no vehicle between the accused’s car and Sgt Zaki’s motorcycle.[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) Sgt Zaki also confirmed that he had full visibility of the accused’s car at the material time.[^5]

17     Sgt Zaki said that when the accused was driving along this side road of Bukit Timah Road near Duke’s road, he saw the accused’s car signal twice for two blinks, before the accused, whose car was slightly in front of the black Honda, made an abrupt lane switch from the extreme left lane to the middle lane of the three lane road. In making the abrupt lane change to the middle lane, the accused drove into a space which was less than one car length in front of the black Honda, which then caused the black Honda to “jam brake”. The black Honda was travelling at the (same) speed of about 60 to 70kmh just before it “jam brake”.

18     Sgt Zaki explained that he concluded that the Honda car had “jam brake” because he saw its red brake light come on for about 1 to 2 seconds, and there was also an obvious dipping motion of the black Honda when it jerked forward because of the hard braking (rather than a casual braking). The black Honda then came to a momentary stop for less than one second before it moved off. The driver of the black Honda did not honk at the accused.

19     Sgt Zaki, confirmed that there was no vehicle between his motorcycle and the black Honda,[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6) and that he had an unobstructed view of the incident.[^7] He further explained that he had assessed the accused to be driving without due care and attention, based on the following considerations:[^8]

> (a)      Abruptness: The accused had made the abrupt lane change, as opposed to a gradual lane change, from the leftmost lane to the middle lane of Bukit Timah Road.

> (b)      Space between the vehicles: When making the lane change, the accused had encroached into the path of the other motorist who was driving the black Honda, when there was less than one car length distance between the accused’s car and the black Honda.

> (c)      Reaction of the driver of the other vehicle: The driver of the black Honda had to “jam brake” i.e. apply the brakes suddenly in order to avoid a collision. As stated earlier, Sgt Zaki observed the black Honda’s brake lights come on, and the car then made a dipping or jerking motion. These resulted from the hard braking action of the driver of the black Honda when the accused’s car changed lane and moved into the same lane as the black Honda. Sgt Zaki observed that the black Honda came to a momentary stop as a result of the hard braking, before it moved off again.

20     When the accused made the abrupt lane change and caused the black Honda to “jam break”, Sgt Zaki said that he “immediately, without a doubt, noted that it’s a careless violation that was committed by the accused. So immediately \[his\] attention…went into stopping the accused to explain the offence.”[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9)Sgt Zaki also said that he had “no doubt that the careless driving had been committed in front of \[him\]”.[^10]

21     Sgt Zaki then attempted to stop the accused. However, as the incident took place at the side road of Bukit Timah Road, and as there were small roads along this side road i.e. at Duke’s Road, Queen’s Road, King’s Road, and Coronation (Walk), there was potentially a lot of vehicles coming out from these areas. Thus, Sgt Zaki had to wait until the side road of Bukit Timah merged into the main Bukit Timah road, so that there would be more space for him to get to the side of the accused’s car in a safe manner. Sgt Zaki said that he needed to do this in order to get the latter’s attention, and then to pull him over to the left side of the road as safely as possible.

22     Sgt Zaki was only able to signal the accused near Tan Kah Kee Drive along the main Bukit Timah Road, as he wanted to make sure that the path was clear and it was safe for him to do so. Sgt Zaki then pulled the accused over at Namly Avenue along the main Bukit Timah Road. There, he explained the offence to the accused.

23     Sgt Zaki said that at that point, the accused insisted that he had not committed any offence. The accused also said that he had seen the black car, and felt that there was enough space to make a proper lane switch before he decided to do so.

24     Sgt Zaki then informed the accused that while he had seen the accused signal before the lane switch, from where Sgt Zaki was, he could see clearly that there was not enough space for the accused to make a proper lane switch, and that he was not satisfied with the abrupt manner in which the accused had carried this out. However, the accused insisted that he had not committed any offence, as he had checked his mirror and blind spot, and had seen the black car. The accused said that he was confident that there was enough space when he made the lane change.

25     Subsequently, Sgt Zaki let the accused go. Sgt Zaki then recorded the details of the accused’s offence in his log sheet (P1). This was done by Sgt Zaki on 11 August 2021 at 0917 hours, using his mobile data terminal, and it was done at the location where he had stopped the accused[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11). _The time of the incident was recorded as having taken place at 0900 hours i.e. less than 20 minutes before Sgt Zaki actually logged down details of the incident in P1_. I have reproduced the relevant extract of P1 below.

![](data:image;base64,)

26     Sgt Zaki also made a report of traffic offence (P4) on the same date (11 August 2021) at 0937 hours. Further, on the same date, Sgt Zaki drew a sketch plan (P2) of the scene, showing the relative positions of the accused’s car and the black Honda, when the accused’s car cut into path of black Honda. Sgt Zaki explained that the sketch plan is a requirement for an officer to come up with for every careless driving offence.[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12)

27     Subsequently, for the court proceedings against the accused, Sgt Zaki prepared a more detailed sketch plan (P3). This was done around 11 October 2021. The detailed sketch plan set out additional information about Sgt Zaki’s location when he saw the commission of the offence, and also the nearby side roads along the part of Bukit Timah Road where the offence occurred.[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13)

28     In court, using a map of the scene, Sgt Zaki marked the positions of his motorcycle, the accused’s car, and the black Honda at various points during the incident, using the following notations (see P5A):

> (a)     X1, Y1 and Z being the locations of Sgt Zaki’s motorcycle, the accused’s car and the black Honda respectively at the time of the offence. This was at side road of Bukit Timah Road towards Upper Bukit Timah Road near Duke’s Road.

> (b)     X2, and Y2 being the locations of his motorcycle and the accused’s car respectively when Sgt Zaki asked the accused to pull over. This was near Tan Kah Kee Drive.

> (c)     X3, and Y3 being the locations of his motorcycle and the accused’s car respectively when the accused was finally pulled over. This was near Namly Avenue.

![](data:image;base64,)

29     Sgt Zaki also testified that he was not able to record the details of the black Honda at that time, although he recognised the make of the car. He said that his main focus after spotting the violation, was to stop the accused in a safe manner, and that this took priority over jotting down the car plate number or other details of the black Honda.

30     Sgt Zaki further described that at the time of the incident, the weather was clear, it was not raining, the road traffic was light, and the road surface was dry. He also said that he did not know the accused personally and had not seen the accused before 11 August 2021, nor at any time after that date. Neither had he checked the accused’s record before he logged the case.[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14)

31     In response to the accused’s questions, Sgt Zaki confirmed that he had had seven hours of rest before he started his shift on 11 August 2021, and that he was not unwell or suffering from any illness on that date.

32     Finally, Sgt Zaki testified that he remembered about this incident as he had originally wanted to make a left turn into Duke’s Road where the neighbourhood police post was, to lodge his earlier summons for the date. However, he had to made a detour instead when he spotted the offence committed by the accused at the side road of Bukit Timah after Duke’s Road. That was why he could clearly remember the location of the offence.[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15)

### Subsequent enforcement action against the accused

33     SSS Sufian is the investigation officer who was assigned the case in February 2022. He testified that the original charge against the accused was amended by the earlier investigation officer who had removed reference to the words “without signal” from the original charge. This happened after the TP had studied the Sgt Zaki’s log sheet (P1) where Sgt Zaki had indicated that the accused did signal at the time of incident.[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

34     SSS Sufian confirmed that based on the First Incident Report (FIR) filed by the reporting officer (RO) i.e. Sgt Zaki, the RO’s log sheet, and the sketch plan, a notice of traffic offence was issued to the accused for the offence. The accused had made several appeals to the TP against the notice of traffic offence, but that after reviews of those appeals, they were rejected by the TP.

### Prosecution’s Submissions

35     Based on the evidence adduced, the Prosecution argued that a reasonable driver would not have made an abrupt lane change with less than a car length distance between his car and the other vehicle, in that such a driver would not have omitted to ensure that there was sufficient space for him to make the lane change. In the present case, as the accused had changed lanes abruptly and encroached into the path of the black Honda, causing the driver of the black Honda to apply his brakes suddenly to avoid a collision, the Prosecution argued that the accused had fallen short of the standard of a reasonable driver. He had thus driven without due care and attention.

## The Defence’s case: Outline of evidence and submissions

### Accused’s denial of the offence

36     The accused testified in his own defence.

37     The accused claimed that, contrary to the evidence of Sgt Zaki, the incident took place on the main Bukit Timah Road near Tan Kah Kee station, and not at the side road near Duke Road as testified to by Sgt Zaki.

38     The accused said that earlier that day, he was driving in his MPV to send his son to school. After that, he was on his way home in his car and had exited Farrer Road to the side road of Bukit Timah road. He described this as a “…three-lane merging, two lanes merging into a lane, and then finally filtering out to Bukit Timah Road.”[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17)

39     After his car had filtered onto the main Bukit Timah road, the accused saw a black Honda car. He described the black Honda to be an MPV like his own car, and not a sedan as stated by Sgt Zaki. The accused said that he was on the left lane of the main Bukit Timah road at that time.

40     As he needed to make a U-turn near where Hwa Chong Institution is to go back to his house at Watten Close, he had to filter to the right lane, starting from where Tan Kah Kee station was. He then described the events as follows:[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18)

> ….my usual practice is to lane change when the car behind me is visible in my rear-view mirror, and that is also why when I---before I did the lane change, I did look at the rear-view mirror, I did see Sgt Zaki behind me. But, I did not know, at that point of time, to be quite honest, that it was a Traffic Police. I did see a motorbike… and that…I did provide---allow sufficient allowance. But, as I’ve said, I do not know whether my usual practice of having a---only doing a lane change when the car is immediately in the visibility of my rear-view mirror is the right way or not, I do not know---hon---honestly. But that is what happened.

> So after the lane change happened, I did---I did another look at the rear-view mirror again … I still take a look, at the rear-view mirror, of which I note---noted, yes, **_there was indeed a slight brake from the car behind_**, from the MPV behind. But it was never a---as what Sgt Zaki described, momentarily stop, and the reason why I---I---am quite sure of that is also because the car---as I said, I did see, and the car also did proceeded to overtake me after I have lane changed, back into the most right lane.

> I also heard a horn, okay. So, when I was on the most right lane, that was when I saw the blinkers from Sgt Zaki, then I realised, oh, that motorbike that I saw earlier in fact was Sgt Zaki, and he turned on the blinkers…

\[emphasis added\]

41     The accused insisted that he did not do anything wrong as he had signalled, checked his blind spot and rear view mirror, and changed lane when it was “good to go”.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19)He also insisted that the incident did not take place near Duke’s road, and that the black Honda was never at the side road of Bukit Timah Road. Further, the accused testified that when Sgt Zaki stopped him and asked him if he had done anything wrong, the accused explained that he had signalled, checked his blind spot and rear view mirror, and only when it was good to go, did he then change lanes.

42     The accused described Sgt Zaki’s reaction as follows:[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20)

> But, his response to me then, was, “You did not signal, and I saw the brake from the car, I---I heard the horn”. And I said---he said that I did not give sufficient allowance, I mean, an abrupt change.

> So I asked, how---”Can you explain to me what---what---you know, what led to that conclusion when you are that far away?” And he said that on the basis of the brake and the horn. That was what he said to me on that day. Never---never in once did he mention that he was able to see accurately the distance that was given to the car.

43     The accused subsequently left for home. Two days later, he received a notice of offence, following which he requested a review by the TP. He subsequently received replies from the TP that the case had been reviewed and that he would have to go to court for the matter.

44     Apart from testifying about what he said had happened, the accused also produced a set of photographs and video clips, which he claimed were re-enactments of events that had taken place on 11th day of August 2021. Their purpose, he explained, was not to replicate the “exact perimeters” but to show that it was difficult for Sgt Zaki to judge whether sufficient allowance had been given when he (the accused) made the lane change.[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21)

45     Amongst other things, the accused said that these exhibits purportedly showed the lane change by his car in front of the black Honda, and also what Sgt Zaki would have seen from his motorcycle behind the accused’s car. The accused said that there was a reasonable doubt as to whether it was possible for Sgt Zaki to have ascertained that the accused’s car was really less than one car length distance from the black Honda at the time of the lane change.

46     The accused, however, accepted that there were limitations to the video clips and photographs, as they did not show or fully reflect the location of the incident,the distance between Sgt Zaki’s motorcycle, the accused’s car or the black Honda on the day in question. Nor were they taken at the same time of the day as the incident, or the road conditions exactly the same. Further, the dimensions and type of vehicles used were not necessarily the same as the black Honda (which he insisted was a MPV) whose lane he had allegedly cut into, nor of the motorcycle driven by Sgt Zaki.[\[note: 22\]](#Ftn_22) In any event, the accused conceded that he was not an expert in scene reconstruction, although he insisted that he knew what had happened that day.[^23]

47     The accused added that since his earlier speeding offence mentioned in his charge, he has taken precautions such as installing a speed detector in his car to limit his speed to 70 kilometres per hour, and that he had not committed any offence since then.

### Accused’s submissions

48     In summing up his case, the accused insisted that if he had committed the present offence, he would have accepted the punishment and merely have had 6 demerit points awarded, rather than challenging the charge in court, and run the risk of being given a one-year suspension. He reiterated that on the material date, he did check his mirror and blind spot, and had signalled before making the lane change. The accused also attempted to cast doubt on whether Sgt Zaki was able to judge if there had been sufficient allowance or not, when the latter said that he had a clear and unobstructed view of the incident.

## The Court’s decision on whether the charge was made out

49     In _Teo Keng Pong v PP_ <span class="citation">\[1996\] 2 SLR(R) 890</span>, Yong Pung How CJ spoke about the Prosecution’s burden of proof at the close of the trial. At \[68\], his Honour said:

> It bears repeating that the burden on the prosecution is to prove its case beyond reasonable doubt. **_It is not to prove the case beyond all doubts. That standard is impossible to achieve in the vast majority of cases_**. In almost all cases, there will remain that minutiae of doubt. ….. **_The question in all cases is whether such doubts are real or reasonable, or whether they are merely fanciful. It is only when the doubts belong to the former category that the prosecution had not discharged its burden_**, and the Accused is entitled to an acquittal.

\[emphasis added\]

50     In the present case, there were two widely conflicting versions presented of events that had taken place that day. One version was given by Sgt Zaki, and the other version by the accused. The main differences between them are summarised below:

### Accused’s offence was clearly observed by Sgt Zaki whose evidence was credible, consistent and corroborated

51     Having carefully reviewed the evidence, which consisted of the testimony of witnesses, as well as documentary, photographic and video evidence tendered, I was of the view that the offence committed by the accused was clearly observed by Sgt Zaki, who gave a clear, credible and believable account of what had happened on the material date. Sgt Zaki’s evidence was also consistent and corroborated. I elaborate on my assessment below.

52     First, I noted that Sgt Zaki had an unimpeded view of events throughout, since it was undisputed that Sgt Zaki was riding in his motorcycle behind the accused at the material time. Further, at the time of the incident, the weather was fine, and there was no issue with lighting, nor any reason to believe that Sgt Zaki’s observation of events was in any way adversely affected, or would be inaccurate or influenced by adverse road, weather or lighting conditions. In fact, the accused himself agreed that on the material date, the weather was clear, the road was dry, and traffic was light. There was, in short, nothing to suggest that Sgt Zaki could not, and did clearly observe the actions of the accused, or the reactions of the driver of the black Honda, at the material time.[\[note: 24\]](#Ftn_24)

53     In this regard, I also noted that Zaki would clearly have had a better view of events than the accused, including of the actions of the accused in driving on the material date and time, and of the reaction of the driver of the black Honda to the accused’s actions, because everything happened literally in front of Sgt Zaki, and at a time when Sgt Zaki was looking straight ahead. Indeed, the accused conceded that Sgt Zaki, who was travelling behind the accused would have had the accused in his line of sight.[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25)In contrast, the accused, who was also looking in the forward direction most of the time, would have had a “poorer view” of the black Honda, as the latter vehicle was behind the accused or at his side, during and after he made the lane switch.

54     Second, I noted that Sgt Zaki’s evidence throughout the trial was consistent, and supported by the contemporaneous records. The latter included:

> (a)     The log sheet (P1) created near the scene of the incident, within 20 minutes of the event. As indicated on P1, Sgt Zaki had noted down what had happened less than 20 minutes prior to the recording he made in P1. Sgt Zaki had noted down the following in P1 (see \[25\] above),:

>> (i)       The lane change by the accused’s car from left to centre (3rd to 2nd) lane, which was done with signalling but without due care;

>> (ii)       That this lane change was carried out with the less than one car length distance between the vehicles;

>> (iii)       That the driver of the black Honda behind the accused’s car had to “jam brake” in response to the accused’s action; and

>> (iv)       The dipping motion of the black Honda because the driver of the black Honda had to “jam his brakes”.

> (b)     P2 – sketch plan by Sgt Zaki which clearly showed the accused’s car to be slightly in front and to the left lane, when it cut into the path of black Honda. This exhibit also showed that Sgt Zaki’s motorcycle was 4 car-lengths behind the accused’s car when he observed the accused making the lane change. This sketch plan was also prepared on the date of the incident, and is a requirement for every TP officer who observes a case of careless driving.[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26)

> (c)     P4 – The FIR filed by Sgt Zaki at 9.37 am, also on the date of the incident.

55     Third, and going back again to why I found Sgt Zaki to be more believable and credible, I noted that Sgt Zaki could clearly and confidently explain that he remembered the location of the incident as being in front of Duke’s Road, because of the location of the Neighbourhood Police Post that he was heading to at that time. His evidence on this aspect provided a strong basis to accept Sgt Zaki’s account of where the incident had taken place, and also the circumstances and manner that it had occurred. In contrast, the accused’s insistence that the incident had taken place at a point further up Bukit Timah Road near Tan Kah Kee station, was based solely on his say so, without any credible explanation or link as to why this was the correct location where it had occurred.

56     Finally, I noted that Sgt Zaki was a trained TP officer of several years’ experience when he observed the accused committing the offence. There was nothing to suggest that he had made a mistake in his observation, or of an error that he may have made when he came up with the contemporaneous records very soon after the event. Sgt Zaki also had no reason to lie, since he did not know accused. I also agreed that there was no suggestion or reason for him to embellish his evidence, nor was there any indication that he had done so. Indeed, the accused agreed that he does not know and had not seen Sgt Zaki before the incident, and there was no reason for Sgt Zaki to have given an untrue account.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27)

57     In contrast to the compelling evidence produced of the accused’s offence, I found it difficult to believe the accused’s account of where the incident happened, the type of car the black Honda was (a MPV or a sedan as mentioned by Sgt Zaki), the distance between his car and the black Honda when his car cut into the latter’s lane, and of the generally exculpatory version that he tried to put across. The accused’s version of events was simply that he had signalled, checked his blind spot and rear view mirror, and that there was sufficient allowance between the vehicles before he made a lane change. He claimed that while the driver of the black Honda had applied his brake, this was not a “jam brake” (hard brake) situation. To the accused’s mind, he essentially did nothing wrong. Yet Sgt Zaki had, out of the blue, pulled him aside and accused him of committing an offence.

58     Further, while the accused had disputed various aspects of Sgt Zaki’s account, including his testimony as to the type of car the black Honda was, the location where the alleged incident took place, whether Sgt Zaki could really see him cut into the Honda car’s path with the vehicles less than one car length apart, and other aspects of Sgt Zaki’s evidence, the fact remained that the accused did have to move his car from the left to right lane in order to make the U turn, and that his car did cut into the black Honda’s lane. In addition, even by the accused’s own account, the driver of the black Honda did have to brake in response to the accused’s actions, although the accused claimed that this was only a gentle braking action (“_a slight brake_”) [\[note: 28\]](#Ftn_28).

59     In addition, unlike Sgt Zaki, I noted that the accused does not have any contemporaneous evidence to support his version of affairs.

60     In this regard, I would add that his “re-enactment” photographs and videos were unhelpful as they were of questionable accuracy or reliability:

> (a)     For one, the accused himself admitted, that he did not replicate the exact same perimeters of the vehicle and conditions at the time of the incident. Hence, his defence exhibits failed to accurately portray the situation, including the conditions and timing of the day, the vehicle dimensions, the type of vehicle involved, the distance between the vehicles at the time of the lane change, or the alleged location of incident, as what Sgt Zaki said he had observed and documented.

> (b)     Further, the accused’s exhibits were also created much later after the incident – including just before the trial commenced (i.e. on 29 May 2022), and in some cases, even after the trial had started (i.e. on 13 July 2022). [\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29) This was in sharp contrast to the contemporaneous records which Sgt Zaki had created on the very day of the incident i.e. on 11th August 2021. Indeed, in the case of the detailed log sheet P1, this record was created by Sgt Zaki within 20 minutes of the offence, and near the scene of the event. As noted above, the exhibits from Sgt Zaki clearly and carefully documented what he had observed of the accused’s actions.

> (c)     In addition, the accused’s exhibits were essentially compiled and created by the accused himself. Not only did he not have experience in creating ‘re-enactments’ of this sort but, being an interested party and one suspected of committing the very offence, he had apparently also not put in any obvious safeguards to ensure the impartiality or independence of the process.

> (d)     Finally, since the accused’s photographs and video re-enactments, were all created sometime after the event, and were _based solely_ on the accused’s own memory of the events that had taken place quite some time before (i.e. on 11th August 2021), rather than being created based on contemporary or independent records or documents, I had additional concerns about their reliability and accuracy.

61     In short, contrary to the accused’s claim that his videos and photos of the supposed re-enactment would support his defence, I was of the respectful view that they were essentially of no real assistance. This was in sharp contrast to the contemporaneous records of Sgt Zaki, which clearly reinforced the evidence against the accused.

62     Finally, to summarise, given that Sgt Zaki, a professional TP officer who was unknown to the accused, was riding behind the accused at about 4 car-lengths distance (or about 6 to 8 metres) behind the accused at the material time, the fact that the incident took place in the daytime in well-lit conditions, and the fact that Sgt Zaki was looking directly ahead all the time and had an unimpeded view of the situation and the actions of the accused and of the reaction of the driver of the black Honda, and that he had recorded his observations almost immediately afterwards, I could not see how Sgt Zaki would have been mistaken and/or given false or inaccurate evidence about the incident. In short, I accepted Sgt Zaki’s clear, coherent, and corroborated evidence that the accused had, using his car, made an abrupt lane change to his right and encroached into the path of the driver of the black Honda, causing the latter to brake suddenly to avoid a collision with the accused’s car.

### Action amounts to driving without due care and attention

63     Having explained why I accepted Sgt Zaki’s account as accurately reflecting the accused’s actions on the date and time in question, the next issue was to decide whether the accused’s actions were sufficient to make out the charge i.e. whether they showed that he had thereby driven without due care and attention in breach of the RTA.

64     In this regard, on whether the accused would be considered to have driven without due care and attention, I accepted as relevant the factors set out by Sgt Zaki. There were also the same factors mentioned by SSS Sufian as being part of the TP protocol to determine if such an offence has been made out.[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30)

65     To reiterated, these factors that both these witnesses mentioned were:

> (a)     the abruptness of the lane change by the accused;

> (b)     the lack of adequate allowance between the accused’s car and the black Honda when the lane change occurred; and

> (c)     the result of the accused’s action on the driver of the black Honda, as shown by the fact that the latter had to react by “jamming brake”, i.e. by his hard and sudden braking, in order to avoid a collision (see \[19\] above).

66     These factors, which I accepted to be present, all showed that the accused had essentially not exercised the caution incumbent upon him, and had not driven with the requisite due care and attention. In short, the Prosecution had successfully proven beyond a reasonable doubt that on the material date, time and location as set out in the charge, the accused had driven without due care and attention when he made the abrupt lane change to his right and encroached into the path of the driver of the black Honda, causing the latter to brake suddenly to avoid a collision with the accused’s car.

67     I was thus satisfied that the charge had been made out, and I convicted the accused on the charge accordingly.

## Sentencing Phase

68     Having found the accused guilty of the offence, I now deal with the issue of sentencing.

### Prescribed punishment and antecedents

69     The prescribed punishment for the charge under s 65(1)(a) punishable under s 65(5)(b) of the RTA is a fine of up to $3,000 or imprisonment for up to 12 months or both. Further, pursuant to s 42(1) RTA, the court may order the accused to be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for life or for such period as the court may think fit.

70     In the present case, the accused admitted to the following traffic related antecedents, which were read out by the Prosecution in court:[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31)

> (a)     On 8th September 2020, he was convicted on one charge under section 63(4) of the RTA in Court 7B and sentenced to a fine of $750 and given 18 demerit points.

> (b)     He also has the following compounded offences under section 120 of the RTA:

>> (i)       On 14th August 2010, he failed to conform to a no U-turn sign for which he paid a composition amount of $70;

>> (ii)       On 19th August 2016, he failed to conform to a red-light signal and paid a composition fine of $200 and was awarded 12 demerit points; and

>> (iii)       On 5th of July 2019, for failing to conform to a no right turn sign, he paid a composition amount of $100.

### Prosecution’s submissions on sentence

71     In its written submissions, the Prosecution sought a fine of at least $1,000, and an order for disqualification against the accused from holding or obtaining a driving license for all classes of vehicles (DQAC) for 12 months. The Prosecution’s submissions can be summarised as follows:

> (a)     Deterrence is the key sentencing consideration for such offences which are difficult to detect and have the potential to cause significant harm. In this regard, s 65(5)(b) of the RTA, was introduced in 2019 to provide enhanced penalties for careless driving offences in order for “stronger deterrence” against irresponsible driving.[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32)

> (b)     The accused was considered a “repeat” offender given his previous conviction in 2020 for an offence under s 63(4) of the RTA. S 65(5)(b) of the RTA was specifically introduced to enhance punishments for such offenders who have repeatedly driven in an irresponsible manner.

> (c)     Given that the accused’s culpability was relatively low and there was no actual harm or collision, a custodial sentence was not sought in the present case. However, a strong deterrent message must still be sent that irresponsible driving would not be condoned, much less for repeat offenders. Thus, a fine of at least $1,000 was appropriate.

> (d)     Further, a period of disqualification from driving was warranted, as irresponsible driving offences have the potential to cause serious harm to other road users. As for the length of disqualification, while there were no reported cases involving offences punishable under s 65(5)(b) RTA, the case of _Kwan Weiguang v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 121</span> (“**_Kwan Weiguang_**”) sets out at \[65\]-\[88\] some factors to be considered in determining the length of any disqualification order, albeit for cases involving dangerous driving where no hurt was caused, and which are punishable under s 64(2C) of the RTA. These factors include the circumstances of the offence (such as the actual and potential harm that could be caused), and the attitude of the driver towards other road users (which includes consideration of the culpability of the driver, especially where road rage was involved).

> (e)     In the present case, while no actual collision resulted, the accused’s abrupt lane change, and his not giving sufficient space to the driver of the black Honda, had caused the latter to brake suddenly to avoid a collision. As such, there was an appreciable level of potential harm that could have been caused. The accused’s actions also reflected a degree of disregard for the safety of other road users.

> (f)     In addition, the accused had displayed prior instances of irresponsible driving, including a conviction in 2020 for speeding which rendered him a repeat offender by virtue of s 65(8) of the RTA. As for compounded offences under the RTA, these could be taken into account as an aggravating factor (citing _Teo Seng Tiong v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGCA 65</span> (“**_Teo Seng Tiong_**_”_)).

> (g)     There was also an unreported case of _PP v Gurjeet Singh Gill_ (SC-907591-2020) (“**_Gurjeet Singh”_**) involving an offender who had fallen asleep while driving and who had lost control of his vehicle, causing it to collide into a tree and a lamppost, and resulting in property damage of around $1,127.47. The offender there was previously traced for drink-driving and careless driving offences, and there were two other charges taken into consideration (TIC) for drink driving and for leaving the scene of the accident. He had pleaded guilty to a charge under s 65(1)(a) RTA punishable under s 65(5)(b) RTA, and was sentenced to a fine of $3,000 and a disqualification period of 12 months.

### Mitigation

72     In mitigation, aside from reiterating that he truly believed that he had not committed the present offence, the accused also said that since the date of his earlier speeding offence conviction in 2020, he had “kept himself clean”.[\[note: 33\]](#Ftn_33) Further, the present offence of careless driving was different from his previous offences (including his compounded offences), which in any event, took place over a span of 21 years.

73     The accused also argued that for the case of _Gurjeet Singh_, where the offender had been sentenced to a fine of $3,000 and a disqualification term of 12 months, there was drink driving involved on the part of the offender. There, the offender had also left the scene of accident after colliding into a tree and lamp post. The accused emphasised that in his case, he had not caused any accident. He had also signalled, and done his checks, and hence should not receive a disqualification order of 12 months.

### Prosecution’s Reply

74     In response, the Prosecution argued that while the accused here was not as culpable as the offender in _Gurjeet Singh_, the latter had pleaded guilty while the accused here has claimed trial. In any event, the Prosecution was seeking a lower fine ($1,000) as compared to that imposed in _Gurjeet Singh_ ($3,000).

75     The Prosecution also denied that a term of 12 months’ DQAC was too high in the present case, since Parliament had specifically amended the RTA to enhance deterrence for irresponsible driving offences. In the present case, the punishment provisions under s 65(5)(b) and s 65A of the RTA were specifically introduced to penalise repeat irresponsible drivers. Thus, deterrence should remain the key sentencing consideration in the present case, given Parliament’s intention, and also the societal need to keep the roads safe for road users.

76     As regards compounded offences, the Prosecution reiterated that based on _Teo Seng Tiong_, the court has the discretion to take into account compounded offences and to decide on the weight to accord to them.

## Decision on Sentence

77     In the present case, the accused was liable for enhanced punishment under s 65(5)(b) of the RTA due to his earlier speeding offence that was set out in the charge. This meant that for the present offence of careless driving, the maximum prescribed punishment was enhanced to a fine not exceeding $3,000, or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months’ imprisonment, or both. Also, as set out in his charge, by virtue of section 42(1) of the RTA, the accused was also liable for disqualification from holding or obtaining a driving licence for life, or for such period as the court may think fit.

78     In the present case, the Prosecution had made reference to the unreported case of _Gurjeet Singh_, where the offender had pleaded guilty to a charge under section 65(1)(a) in a situation where he was similarly liable for enhanced punishment under s 65(5)(b) of the RTA. There, the offender was sentenced to a fine of $3,000 in default 10 days imprisonment, and disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for 12 months.

79     While I recognised that there are limitations to the extent to which reliance could be made to unreported decisions which are devoid of reasoning, for the _Gurjeet Singh_ case, I was at least provided with the relevant papers that were tendered at the _Gurjeet Singh’s_ plead guilty mention. From these papers, I could derive information that was useful for the purpose of comparing the facts and situation in _Gurjeet Singh_ with those in the present case.

80     In this regard, I noted that the particulars of the offender’s charge in _Gurjeet Singh_ was that he had failed to have proper control of his vehicle which resulted in it veering to the right, mounting the centre road divider and colliding onto a lamp post and a tree. In sentencing him, the court had also taken into account two TIC charges, namely for drink driving, and for failing to stop after a traffic accident respectively.

81     Based on the information available to me, I agreed with the accused that the overall circumstances of _Gurjeet Singh_ were more serious than those in the present case, not least because no actual accident was caused in the present case. That said, the latter may well have more to do with the quick reaction of the driver of the black Honda in the present case, rather than with the accused’s actions, as it was the former who had to brake hard to avoid a collision when the accused’s car made the abrupt lane change and cut into the path of the black Honda. Nevertheless, the fact remained that no actual harm resulted from the accused’s actions in the present case, and I was prepared to consider this factor in the accused’s favour. Further, I noted that in _Gurjeet Singh’s_ case, there was drink driving involved, and there were also other charges taken into consideration, whereas the accused here only faced a single charge.

82     However, there were also factors that were more aggravating in the present case as compared with the circumstances in _Gurjeet Singh_.

> (a)     For one, in _Gurjeet Singh_, the offender had pleaded guilty, and hence presumably would have received a sentencing discount for taking that course of action. In contrast, the accused here claimed trial, and hence was not entitled to any such sentencing discount.

> (b)     Moreover, the accused in the present case had committed his careless driving offence on 11th August 2021, which was less than a year after his conviction in 3 November 2020 for speeding, the latter being the very reason for his enhanced punishment for the present charge. In contrast, the offender in _Gurjeet Singh_ had committed his careless driving offence on 7 March 2020, while his previous conviction mentioned in his charge, had taken place much earlier on 23 July 2013. Thus, the accused here has a more recent history of violation of the RTA, than the offender in _Gurjeet Singh_.

83     All things considered, I was of the view that a fine of $1,000 sought by the Prosecution, which was only one-third of the amount imposed in _Gurjeet Singh_, was an appropriate quantum. This sum was also just $250 more than the fine the accused had received for the speeding offence that he was convicted of less than a year before the commission of his present offence of careless driving.

84     As for the disqualification order sought in the case, I considered the guidance of Aedit Abdullah J in _Kwan Weiguang_. There, his Honour had discussed about the objectives of disqualification orders as follows:

> \[59\] A driving disqualification order combines three sentencing objectives: punishment, protection of the public and deterrence (_Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Edwin Nathen_”) at \[13\]). Often, due to the limited range of fines in the punishment provision, the impact of a disqualification order is likely to be felt much more acutely than any marginal increase in the quantum of the fine (see _Edwin Nathen_ at \[13\]).

> ….

> \[62\]  A disqualification order also serves to remove the privilege to drive from those who have abused it, and this also reinforces the notion of shared usage of the roads. It must be remembered that driving is an inherently dangerous activity….

85     In _Kwan Weiguang_, the offender had pleaded guilty to driving his vehicle in a dangerous manner by repeatedly changing lanes ahead of another motor car, and subsequently applying his brake and coming to a rest in a position likely to cause danger to other road users on lane 2 of 3 lanes. In deciding on the appropriate punishment, Aedit Abdullah J considered that there was danger posed to other road users by the offender’s aggressive driving, especially as it was drizzling at the time and the road surface was wet. The offender’s actions also showed him to be a road bully as they were directed at a motorist who had earlier high-beamed the offender. In the offender’s favour, the Court considered that he had a clean driving record, and was untraced even for compounded offences. Further, the offender had pleaded guilty, and readily admitted fault and owned up to being impulsive at the time of the incident.

86     Taking into account the relevant sentencing factors, the High Court there reduced the offender’s disqualification term from 15 months to 12 months. At \[99\] of the report, Aedit Abdullah J explained:

> Taking all the circumstances into account, most significantly, that this was a road rage incident with danger being posed to road users, a disqualification order of 12 months’ duration is appropriate to fulfil the objectives of punishment, protection of the public and deterrence.

87     In the present case, I accepted that there was danger posed to other road users, in particular, to the driver (and passengers, if any) of the black Honda, as the latter vehicle could have collided into the accused’s car due to the abrupt lane change made by the accused, which resulted in his car encroaching into the path of the black Honda. The accused’s action had caused the driver of the black Honda to have to brake suddenly to avoid a collision. Moreover, the accused here had contested the charge, for which he would not be entitled to any sentencing discount for pleading guilty. This was dissimilar to the situation in both the cases of _Gurjeet Singh_ and _Kwan Weiguang_, where the offenders had pleaded guilty and had admitted to their respective offences.

88     Furthermore, due to his speeding offence for which he was convicted on 3 November 2020, the accused here faced enhanced punishment under s 65(5)(b) of the RTA. As highlighted by the Prosecution, based on _Teo Seng Tiong_, aside from his previous conviction for the speeding offence, the accused’s compounded offences including his relatively recent compounded offences in 2016 and 2019 (see \[70(b)(ii) and 70(b)(iii)\] above) could be considered in sentencing. That said, I did not consider them to be of major significance in determining the duration of the disqualification order.

89     In the accused’s favour, I did not consider the danger posed by him in the present case to be as great as that posed in either _Gurjeet Singh_ or _Kwan_ Weiguang. Nor were the circumstances of the offence here as serious as the offences in either of the two cited cases. This was especially so in the case of _Gurjeet Singh_, which involved drink driving, actual damage being caused and also an additional two TIC charges. As for _Kwan Weiguang_, the offender had faced a heavier charge and his case also involved elements of road rage.

90     Accordingly, I was of the view that while a significant period of disqualification should be imposed in light of the reasons set out in \[87\] and \[88\], the duration of disqualification should be lower than the 12-month period imposed in _Gurjeet Singh_ or _Kwan Weiguang_.

91     All in all, taking everything into account, I was of the view that a disqualification order of 10 months would, in the words of Aedit Abdullah J at \[99\] of _Kwan Weiguang_, be “…appropriate to fulfil the objectives of punishment, protection of the public and deterrence”.

92     Thus, the final sentence imposed was a fine of $1,000 (in default 5 days imprisonment) and an order of disqualification against the accused holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of ten(10) months. The accused has paid his fine and commenced serving his disqualification term.
